    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Stand By Your Man, the Original</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Scott R Fahnestock letter on Kate Zernike's October 19 article recalls Rose Ponzi, who defended her husband, Charles, during Boston's Ponzi scandal in 1920</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''The Wifely Art of Standing By'' is nothing new. Consider this wifely quotation:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''The Wifely Art of Standing By'' is nothing new. Consider this wifely quotation:</p>
        <p>''He is my husband. My faith in my husband is as unshaken as it was before. His mother is as certain of his innocence as I am. Why wouldn't we be? Who knows Charlie better than we?'' This was Mrs. Rose Ponzi, age 18, as quoted in The Boston Post, Aug. 13, 1920, upon the arrest of her husband, Charles K. Ponzi, who bilked Boston for more than $10 million (in 1920 dollars!).</p>
        <p>SCOTT R. FAHNESTOCK  Cincinnati</p>
      </block>
